 George W. Bush's 3,351 remarks during his first term? Did all these words matter? The Politics of Economic Leadership is the first comprehensive effort to examine when, why, and how presidents talk about the economy, as well as whether the president's economic rhetoric matters. It demonstrates conclusively that such presidential words do matter. Using an unprecedented compendium of every known unique statement by U.S. presidents about the economy from World War II through the first George W. Bush administration, Dan Wood measures the relative intensity and optimism of presidents' economic rhetoric. His pathbreaking statistical analysis shows that presidential words can affect everything from approval of the president's job performance to perceptions of economic news, consumer confidence, consumer behavior, business investment, and interest rates. The impacts are both immediate and gradual. Ultimately, Wood concludes, rhetoric is indeed a tool of presidential leadership that can be used unilaterally to affect a range of political and economic outcomes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Executive Branch.2bisacsh  aAnnual Economic Report of the President.  aBarrett, Andrew.  aBlumenthal, Sidney.  aBrace, Paul.  aBureau of Economic Analysis.  aBureau of the Budget.  aCanes-Wrone, Brandice.  aChappell, Henry W.  aClark, Harold D.  aCouncil of Economic Advisors.  aDruckman, James N.  aEconomic Report to Congress.  aErickson, Robert S.  aFederal Reserve Board.  aGDP (Gross Domestic Product).  aGergen, David.  aGreat Depression.  aGreenstein, Fred.  aGross Domestic Product (GDP).  aHeclo, Hugh.  aHinckley, Barbara.  aIran hostage crisis.  aJacobs, Lawrence R.  aKeech, William P.  aKernell, Samuel J.  aKeynesian economics.  aMachiavel